<TITLE> Stocks on the rebound </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Sept 30 (bdnews24.com) -- Stocks rebounded after four days of losses Sunday, paced by market leaders in the banking, cement and pharmaceuticals sectors. The market declined in the first half of trading but recovered gradually to end higher, although losers outnumbered gainers. "The market buoyed as stocks with big market capitalisation gained significantly," said Manira Khan, an investment associate with Equity Partners Ltd. The DGEN or general index finished on 2548.18, up 3.28 points or 0.12 percent on the previous day. The DSI or all-share price index added 5.99 points or 0.28 percent to end on 2108.48. The DSE-20 blue-chip index fell 5.72 points or 0.28 percent to finish on 2002.61. Of the issues traded, 114 gained 63 dropped and 22 held steady. Turnover stood at Tk 1.15 billion from 13,510,541 traded shares. Summit Power, a market leader in turnover, lost 0.85 percent to end on Tk 1422.25. The fall followed an offer by one of its sponsors, Summit Industrial and Mercantile Corporation, to sell 250,000 of its shares. Summit Industrial sold 200,000 of its shares last week. Power Grid Company of Bangladesh, the third biggest share by market capitalisation, also ended slightly lower. DESCO gained. BRAC Bank, the second most active issue, regained pace adding 1.06 percent to end on Tk 1276.25. AB Bank finished up 1.40 percent to end on Tk 2379.25. Most mutual funds declined amid profit-taking. AIMS 1st MF, the most active mutual fund, dipped 0.64 percent to Tk 7.71. Phoenix Finance and Investment, which debuted last week, fell 5.95 percent to Tk 399. Cement stocks advanced, led by Lafarge Surma Cement which has the biggest issue by market capitalisation. Heidelberg Cement also gained. Square Pharma recovered some losses. Other pharmaceuticals issues also moved up. Lexco, Peoples Insurance and Rose Heaven Ball led the gainers. Bangladesh Lamps, 6th ICB MF and Asia Pacific Insurance were the main losers. All indices on the Chittagong Stock Exchange, except the CSE-30 blue-chip index, finished up. Of the issues traded, 57 advanced, 36 fell and six ended unchanged. bd
